Meaning that before nisp the usage is minimum and would all together be absent if there is more flow restriction.

column121: 0.3 for low flow rock technical, over 5 ft for big water experience
column124: 5.5ft currently for Pineview, 6ft for Bridges, 6.5ft and higher may be getting into troubles with the bridges on bridges.
column125: Typical high usage levels for this stretch is 2-3.5ft.  By the time 4ft his reached the number of people seen starts dropping.  Bridges at 4ft I don't see as much harder than 3.5ft.   Bridges at 5ft turns into a harder river.  Still fun in a playboat or larger, but bigger holes, grabbier water, more consequences.  Though still a solid IV run.   By 5.5ft Killer bridge is too low for a framed raft w/chair.  ones w/o chairs can slip under.
column155: 6+?  The biggest question is when the bridges become too low for a kayak.
column156: In general this run to me is hardest in the 4ft range.   Above 4 and you can sneak any hard rapid.   A competent class 3 boater could technically do it, but a mistake could be a long swim especially at 5ft+.  Though at higher flows, making the takeout eddy at Pineview putin is a bit more challenging.
column181: I've done the full run once at 0.7ish feet.
column187: More water is more fun!   5+ definitely gives some big holes to avoid.
column212: 0.75 I think is my lowest float.  Mish falls is not great.
column218: Great section, second favorite stretch after bridges on the lower poudre.   Most rapids get easier at high water (4.5ft+) with clear sneaks.  But big holes at that flow.    This stretch is the most dangerous on the lower poudre at high water.  3-Way turns into an almost river wide hole that will hold a kayak, and can hold a raft at 5+ flows.   It's more consequential than PineView at those flows.  You can run right and left safely, but keep out of the middle in a kayak.
column243: If you're willing to walk a few stretches 0ft.  If not, 0.5ft
column244: 0.5 for Middle, Upper, 1ft for lower (since airplane rock moved)
column247: Depends on the section.  Upper > 2ft.  Middle > 3ft.  Lower >2.5ft
column249: This stretch is really 3 different runs.   Middle Narrows (below White Line to top of Lower (bridge)) is an amazing class IV run.  Great rapids, great play.  Excellent creeking, eddy hopping.  Stellar.  Wish it was more than 1 mile.    Lower narrows and upper narrows are class Vs.  They will range from V-/IV+ at low flows (0-2ft) to V/V+ at 6ft.      This stretch I don't see as being a great raft stretch.  Though I have seen them on it and occasionally see IKs too.
column274: For the whole run, probably 2.5.   Grandpa's Gorge to Eggers is a great play run at 1.5ft though
column279: Unsure.   At 6ft is was a blast.
column280: If you put in at Indian Meadows, the biggest issue with high water may be the bridge at Foo Fang/Death by Dismemberment.    But at 6ft, it's still fine.   This drop is somewhat harder around 4ft than at 5 or 6ft.     Entire run is great.  More water, more fun.  If the river is above 4ft and I have the time, I'd rather run either of the Rustics than anything in the lower canyon.   Running both of the rustics makes a great 16mile class IV run at 4ft or higher.
column309: Unknown.  6ft is a blast and that's the highest I've experienced
column311: White Mile (Home Moraine to ~mm 87 or 89 I forget which) at high water could be a bad swim.  Big holes, big waves, very continuous.  This is the most difficult stretch.  Put in below it if not a solid IV.      The highway 14 bridge is a hazard for rafts above 5ft.  Either portage or line the raft on river left.   At 6ft it's getting uncomfortable in a kayak.  Stay left.    This is my favorite stretch of river at 4ft and higher.  Some good surf at all levels, just bring the appropriate boat (playboat <4.5ft, creeker >4.5ft).  Great scenery, challenging rapids, such fun.      combining this with Lower makes a great 16 mile run.  Stop for a lunch break somewhere in Indian Meadows.
